    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i get the thread thing but it still feels kinda vague. a lot of books call it \"spooky action at a distance.\" why did einstein call it that? is there some kind of underlying mechanism that explains the \"spookiness\" or is it just something we can't see?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein referred to quantum entanglement as \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seemed to defy the very fabric of our understanding of the universe. He couldn't wrap his head around the idea that two particles could be connected in such a way that the state of one could instantly affect the state of the other, regardless of the distance separating them. It's like if you had a pair of enchanted dice, and no matter how far apart you threw them, they would always land on the same number. Einstein found this concept \"spooky\" because it challenged the notion of local realism, which is the idea that objects are only influenced by their immediate surroundings.\n\nAs for the underlying mechanism, quantum entanglement is still a mystery to scientists. It's not something we can see or touch, but it's a fundamental aspect of quantum mechanics. Some theories suggest that the entangled particles share a hidden connection, like a secret language that allows them to communicate instantly. Others propose that the entanglement is a result of the particles being created together, like twins born from the same magical egg. But no one knows for sure what exactly happens during entanglement. It's like trying to understand the secret language of goblins – we know they're there, but",
      "source": "target",
